titleMetadata.aimsAndScope:
&lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt; is an international peer-reviewed journal addressing the policy implications of energy supply and use from their economic, social, planning and environmental aspects. Papers may cover global, regional, national, or even local topics that are of wider policy significance, and of interest to international agencies, governments, public and private sector entities, local communities and non-governmental organisations. Within this broad spectrum, topics of particular interest include energy and environmental regulation, energy supply security, the quality and efficiency of energy services, the effectiveness of market-based approaches and/or governmental interventions, technological innovation and diffusion, and voluntary initiatives where the broader policy implications can be recognised. Policy prescriptions are required to be supported by rigorous analysis and balanced appraisal.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; Given the aims and scope of Energy Policy, all submitted papers should explicitly address policy issues involving energy supply or use.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; This journal welcomes contributions that support and advance the UN's &lt;a href="https://sdgresources.relx.com/"&gt;sustainable development goals&lt;/a&gt;, in particular SDG 7 (Affordable and clean energy).&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Special issue proposals&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Prospective guest editor(s) should submit written proposals that incorporate the rationale for the special issue topic, positions it in the literature, and include some illustrative topics and proposed contributors. Guest Editors should complete and submit this &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/__data/promis_misc/EnergyPolicy-SpecialIssueProposalForm.docx"&gt;Special Issue Proposal template&lt;/a&gt; to be considered for publication in the Journal.

members.biography:
Dr. Leila Dagher is an Associate Professor of Economics at the American University of Beirut (AUB), Economic Adviser to the Lebanese Minister of Economy, Minister of Industry, and Minister of Foreign Affairs, and has been an adjunct lecturer at the George Washington University (GWU) since 2016. Prior to her current appointment, she previously served in various capacities; economic adviser to the former Prime Minister, former Deputy Prime Minister, former Minister of Economy, and former Minister of Foreign Affairs, Director of the Institute of Financial Economics (AUB), and chairperson of the Department of Economics (AUB). 
Dr. Dagher&rsquo;s research applies her econometric knowledge to the areas of energy, environmental, and financial economics with a focus on producing policy-relevant studies. She has written extensively on the energy-economic growth nexus, oil price shocks, and green power markets. Her work has appeared in leading academic journals such as the Energy Journal, Resources Policy, Quarterly Review of Economics and Finance and others. Dr. Dagher has been a visiting scholar at various higher education and research institutions including Harvard&rsquo;s Kennedy School of Government. She currently serves on editorial boards for Energy Policy, Finance Research Letters, and Utilities Policy. Dr. Dagher is a Senior Fellow at the Lebanese Center for Policy Studies and serves on the steering committee of the Mashreq Gender Facility. She received her Bachelor of Engineering from the American University of Beirut and her Ph.D. in Mineral Economics from the Colorado School of Mines.
 &lt;a href="https://www.aub.edu.lb/fas/economics/Pages/leiladagher.aspx"&gt;Editor's Personal Website&lt;/a&gt;

Dr. Jessika Bohlmann holds a PhD in Economics from the University of Pretoria. She previously completed a Bachelor of Economics from Monash University and a Master of Commerce from the University of Pretoria. In addition, she completed Certificate Courses in Regional and Dynamic Computable General Equilibrium Modelling presented by the Centre of Policy Studies in Melbourne, and an Advanced Certificate Course in Emerging Markets and Risk Analysis from Fordham University in New York.  

Dr. Bohlmann is currently appointed as a Research Specialist in the Faculty of Economic and Management Sciences at the University of Pretoria where she works at the Office of the Dean collaborating with various research-related tasks and projects, and teaches occasional postgraduate courses in the School of Public Management and Administration. Dr. Bohlmann&rsquo;s main areas of expertise include the use of computable general equilibrium and econometric models for practical policy research, particularly in the fields of energy and environmental economics and sectoral impact analysis. Further to her appointment at the University of Pretoria, Dr. Bohlmann is also contracted as a Consultant for the Partnership for Economic Policy, serves on the Council of the South African Association for Energy Economics, and acts as a referee for various academic journals.
 &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/home"&gt;Editor's Personal Website&lt;/a&gt;

Huntington is Executive Director of Stanford University's Energy Modeling Forum, where he conducts studies to improve the usefulness of models for understanding energy and environmental problems.  In 2005 the Forum received the prestigious Adelman-Frankel Award from the International Association for Energy Economics for its &quot;unique and innovative contribution to the field of energy economics.&quot;
His current research interests are modeling energy security, energy price shocks, energy market impacts of environmental policies, and international natural gas and LNG markets.  In 2002 he won the Best Paper Award from the Energy Journal. 
He is a Senior Fellow and a past-President of the United States Association for Energy Economics and was a member of the National Petroleum Council.  He was also Vice-President for Publications for the International Association for Energy Economics and a member of the American Statistical Association's Committee on Energy Data.  Previously, he served on a joint USA-Russian National Academy of Sciences Panel on energy conservation research and development. Huntington has testified before the U.S. Senate Committee on Foreign Relations and the California Energy Commission. Prior to coming to Stanford in 1980, he held positions in the corporate and government sectors with Data Resources Inc., the U.S. Federal Energy Administration, and the Public Utilities Authority in Monrovia, Liberia (as a U.S. Peace Corps Volunteer).
 &lt;a href="https://emf.stanford.edu/"&gt;Editor's Personal Website&lt;/a&gt;

items.description:
&lt;p&gt;The energy transition and the electrification of the heating and transport sectors will require a more active participation of the demand side to balance fluctuating renewable energy supply with demand and reduce the need for grid expansion. In addition, the energy crisis has revealed important shortcomings in the current design of electricity tariffs. Customers paying real-time prices have experienced excessive bill increases that led to regulatory interventions in the form of compensations. Customers on fixed-price contracts, on the other hand, had insufficient incentives to reduce their load.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Future-proof electricity tariffs should provide a solution to all these challenges. They should protect customers from excessive price peaks but still retain incentives for demand response and enable customers to specify the amount of flexibility which they are able to provide and ensure that this flexibility is used optimally. In addition, the regulation for retailers needs to be revised, to enable competition without undermining the incentives to hedge against increasingly volatile prices.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Guest editors:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dr. Sigurd Bjarghov, PhD&lt;br&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;SINTEF Energy Research, Trondheim, Norway&lt;br&gt;(grid tariff design, demand response, market design, local flexibility markets)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dr. Christine Gschwendtner, PhD&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;Harvard Kennedy School, Harvard University, Cambridge, USA&lt;br&gt;(electrification, flexibility, demand-side management, distribution grids)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dr. David Ribo-Perez, PhD&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;Faculty of Technology, Policy and Management, TU Delft, Delft, Netherlands&lt;br&gt;(electricity market design, electricity tariffs, consumer-centered energy systems, flexibility)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dr. Tim Schittekatte, PhD&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;Sloan School of Management, MIT/Florence School of Regulation, Cambridge, USA&lt;br&gt;(regulation, power markets, energy economics)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dr. Christian Winzer, PhD&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;Center for Energy and Environment, School of Management and Law, Zurich University of Applied Sciences/ZHAW, Zurich, Switzerland&lt;br&gt;(electricity tariffs, grid tariffs, market design, demand response)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dr. Selin Yilmaz, PhD&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;Department of Energy Efficiency, University of Geneva, Geneva, Switzerland&lt;br&gt;(electricity tariffs, flexibility, demand response, governance, social acceptance)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Electricity tariffs are becoming a critical policy issue as the needs to electrify demand increase and our distribution networks reach unprecedented levels of congestion. The expected new loads comprise heat pumps, electric vehicles, rooftop solar, and batteries. While previous demand was rather inflexible, these new distributed energy resources can behave flexibly and provide some of the flexibility that is needed to accommodate renewables and defer network investments. Future electricity tariffs should aim to facilitate this role while providing the necessary protection for vulnerable consumers from the full risk of volatile electricity prices. The high policy relevance of tariff design is underlined by the responses of ACER and ENTSO-E to the EU consultation on future market design, both of which highlighted tariff design as a key topic for future reforms, as well as by the large amount of ongoing research in response to the energy crisis (see &lt;a href="https://www.esig.energy/aligning-retail-pricing-with-grid-needs/"&gt;White-Paper Series&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://pure.uvt.nl/ws/portalfiles/portal/65524792/CERRE_Retail_Energy_Markets_Under_Stress.pdf"&gt;Report1&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://ceepr.mit.edu/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/MIT-CEEPR-RC-2023-01.pdf"&gt;Report2&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Special Issue “Future Electricity Tariffs” aims to improve the design and implementation of electricity tariffs. Tariffs results from a complex decision-making process as different objectives (cost recovery, efficiency, simplicity, and transparency...) tend to conflict with each other and different consumer groups may be affected in different ways by different designs. The process should therefore be addressed and analysed with a transdisciplinary approach to deal with all issues arising (quantitative, qualitative, policy design, design of indicators...). We invite submissions on the following topics:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Grid charges, energy charges and interactions between them&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Distribution network tariffs&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Congestion management mechanisms at the distribution level&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Tariffs for different security levels (or service priority)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Different approaches for risk hedging&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Retail competition and rules for tariff switching&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Financial hedging requirements for suppliers and other regulatory aspects&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Attractiveness of tariffs for users&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manuscript submission information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You are invited to submit your manuscript at any time before the submission deadline of &lt;strong&gt;July 31, 2023&lt;/strong&gt;. For any inquiries about the appropriateness of contribution topics, please contact &lt;a href="mailto:FutureElectricityTariffs@gmail.com"&gt;FutureElectricityTariffs@gmail.com&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unless the answer is straightforward, we will answer your request latest after the next monthly meeting of the organizing committee.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The journal’s submission platform (&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.editorialmanager.com/jepo/default1.aspx" target="_blank"&gt;Editorial Manager®&lt;/a&gt;) will be available for receiving submissions to this Special Issue. Please refer to the &lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.elsevier.com/journals/energy-policy/0301-4215/guide-for-authors" target="_blank"&gt;Guide for Authors&lt;/a&gt; to prepare your manuscript and select the article type of “&lt;strong&gt;VSI: FET&lt;/strong&gt;” when submitting your manuscript online on the submission platform. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Keywords:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Electricity tariffs, grid charges, network regulation, retail tariffs, retailer regulation, energy transition, demand response&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn more about the benefits of publishing in a special issue: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interested in becoming a guest editor? Discover the benefits of guest editing a special issue and the valuable contribution that you can make to your field: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There is an urgent demand for research supporting the development of new policy frameworks for energy saving and conservation. Artificial Intelligence and Data Science advances are augmenting the ability to make decisions by leveraging the power of advanced analytics and collective intelligence. It is now possible to understand how people are being made aware of new energy solutions and their advantages for environmental sustainability. Text mining and social network analysis can support the development and diffusion of new energy policies, technologies, and sustainable business strategies. We solicit original research on big data methods and tools to support the decisions of policymakers and companies operating in the energy ecosystem.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Guest editors:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prof. Andrea Fronzetti Colladon, PhD &lt;br&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;University of Perugia, Perugia, Italy&lt;br&gt;(Social Network Analysis, Text Mining, Big Data Analytics, Organizational Communication and Behavior, Collaborative Innovation Networks)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prof. Anna Laura Pisello, PhD&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;University of Perugia, Perugia, Italy&lt;br&gt;(Energy efficiency, Environmental Comfort, Energy Transition, Climate Change Mitigation)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prof. Luisa F. Cabeza, PhD&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;University of Lleida, Lleida, Spain&lt;br&gt;(Energy storage, Life Cycle Assessment, Climate Change, Energy Efficiency, Energy Transition)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The special issue covers the topics below.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;- Global, regional, national, or even local studies of policy significance and of interest to international agencies, governments, public and private sector entities, local communities, and non-governmental organizations&lt;br&gt;- Using data science to support the green energy transition&lt;br&gt;- Using AI and big data analytics to evaluate the impact generated by policies on user behavior and well-being&lt;br&gt;- Using text mining and natural language processing for the analysis of the green energy discourse&lt;br&gt;- AI, machine learning methods, and social network analysis applied to the energy transition&lt;br&gt;- Monitoring societal awareness and acceptance of green energy solutions and new dedicated policies&lt;br&gt;- Sensor data analysis and Internet of Things in the energy ecosystem&lt;br&gt;- Understanding the role of the digital economy (and e-gov) in facilitating the energy transition&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manuscript submission information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You are invited to submit your manuscript before&lt;strong&gt; Sep 4th, &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2023&lt;/strong&gt;. The submission portal will be open by the end of April. Any questions about the special issue can be directed to the Managing Guest Editor &lt;strong&gt;Andrea Fronzetti Colladon &lt;/strong&gt;(andrea.fronzetticolladon@unipg.it).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The journal’s submission platform (&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.editorialmanager.com/jepo/default1.aspx" target="_blank"&gt;Editorial Manager®&lt;/a&gt;) will be available for receiving submissions to this Special Issue. Please refer to the &lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.elsevier.com/journals/energy-policy/0301-4215/guide-for-authors" target="_blank"&gt;Guide for Authors&lt;/a&gt; to prepare your manuscript and select the article type of “&lt;strong&gt;VSI: Boost energy transition&lt;/strong&gt;” when submitting your manuscript online on the submission platform. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Keywords:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;- Clean Energy Transition&lt;br&gt;- Data Science&lt;br&gt;- Text Mining&lt;br&gt;- Social Network Analysis&lt;br&gt;- AI&lt;br&gt;- Climate Change Resilience&lt;br&gt;- Energy Efficiency&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn more about the benefits of publishing in a special issue: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interested in becoming a guest editor? Discover the benefits of guest editing a special issue and the valuable contribution that you can make to your field: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Household energy consumption and climate change are highly related. On the one hand, residential energy sector has become a major energy consumption sector, responsible for significant emissions of carbon dioxide (CO2) (Mi et al., 2020). According to the International Energy Agency (IEA) data, residents consumed 21% of global total final energy in 2019 (IEA, 2022). On the other hand, climate change has impacts on household energy consumption. Global temperature rise will increase energy demand for cooling and decrease energy demand for heating. In addition, household energy consumption is known to affect human well-being and can result in harmful environmental impacts. Thus, understanding the changes and dynamics of household energy consumption as well as the associated greenhouse gas emission and environmental impacts at the global and regional level will be critical for achieving climate change mitigation targets.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Guest editors:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prof. Dr. Zhifu Mi, PhD&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;University College London, London, UK&lt;br&gt;(Climate change economics, energy policy, carbon neutrality)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dr. Lu Jiang, PhD&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Beijing Normal University, Beijing, China&lt;br&gt;(Energy geography, regional sustainability, energy consumption)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Recent work has identified several critical factors that affect the consumption of household energy, including household characteristics, energy prices, and energy-related policies (Wolske et al., 2020; Wu et al., 2017; Zhou et al., 2016). Therefore, the type and amount of household energy consumption are different within and across regions and nations. In the coming years, household energy transition requires further development to achieve policy objectives and function well in climate change mitigation (Mi et al., 2020).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The special issue “Household energy consumption and climate change” aims to improve understanding on the regional diversity and effects of relevance to energy consumption in our households. This issue will provide a platform for cross-cutting analyses that inform global, national and regional climate change mitigation targets. It will provide critical advices for key stakeholders such as policy makers, practitioner, industries and households. Hence, we invite submissions on the following topics:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;1. Household energy use and environmental impacts&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;- Residential mobility, space heating, and cooling energy demand&lt;br&gt;- Ecology and climate consequences of energy use&lt;br&gt;- Environmental impacts of energy use&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;2. Household energy efficiency and energy conservation&lt;br&gt;- Household energy consumption behaviors&lt;br&gt;- The rebound effect on energy efficiency&lt;br&gt;- Technology innovation and household energy consumption&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;3. Energy poverty and energy justice&lt;br&gt;- Definitions and methodological aspects of energy poverty&lt;br&gt;- The relationship between energy poverty, poverty and inequality&lt;br&gt;- Energy inequity and health risk&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;4. Household energy consumption and climate change governance&lt;br&gt;- Energy transition and renewable energy&lt;br&gt;- Urbanization and household energy consumption&lt;br&gt;- Household energy consumption and climate change management&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;5. Household energy demand in a warming world&lt;br&gt;- Impacts of global warming on household heating and cooling energy&lt;br&gt;- Forecasting of household energy demand&lt;br&gt;- Structural upgrading of household energy&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Manuscript submission information:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You are invited to submit your manuscript at any time before the submission deadline of &lt;strong&gt;July 31, 2023&lt;/strong&gt;. For any inquiries about the appropriateness of contribution topics, please contact Executive Guest Editor &lt;strong&gt;Zhifu Mi &lt;/strong&gt;via z.mi@ucl.ac.uk&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The journal’s submission platform (&lt;a href="https://www.editorialmanager.com/jepo/default2.aspx"&gt;Editorial Manager®&lt;/a&gt;) is available for receiving submissions to this Special Issue. Please refer to the &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/journals/energy-policy/0301-4215/guide-for-authors"&gt;Guide for Authors&lt;/a&gt; to prepare your manuscript. When submitting your manuscripts, please choose "&lt;strong&gt;VSI: Household energy&lt;/strong&gt;" from the dropdown menu.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;References:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;IEA (International Energy Agency) .2022. Data and statistics. https://www.iea.org/data-and-statistics/data-browser/?country=WORLD&amp;fuel=Energy%20consumption&amp;indicator=TFCShareBySector. Accessed 28 April 2022&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Mi, Z., Zheng, J., Meng, J., Ou, J., Hubacek, K., Zhu Liu, D’Maris Coffman, Nicholas Stern, Sai Liang &amp; Yi-Ming Wei.,2020. Economic development and converging household carbon footprints in China, Nature Sustainability 3(7). 529-537&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Wolske, K. S., Gillingham, K. T., &amp; Schultz, P. 2020. Peer influence on household energy behaviours. Nature Energy, 5(3), 202-212.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Wu, S., Zheng, X., &amp; Wei, C. 2017. Measurement of inequality using household energy consumption data in rural China. Nature Energy, 2(10), 795-803.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Zhou, K., &amp; Yang, S. 2016. Understanding household energy consumption behavior: The contribution of energy big data analytics. Renewable and Sustainable Energy Reviews, 56, 810-819.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Keywords:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Household energy, Climate change, Energy efficiency, Energy demand, Energy poverty, Energy justice&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn more about the benefits of publishing in a special issue: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interested in becoming a guest editor? Discover the benefits of guest editing a special issue and the valuable contribution that you can make to your field: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

items.intro:
&lt;p&gt;Rising energy and housing costs for poor households have fueled energy policy debate in recent years. The availability of affordable, reliable, and sustainable energy service are essential to sustain well-being, which is also a prerequisite for achieving SDG7 and specific other SDGs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Further, reliable access to energy services is crucial for reducing various forms of poverty and sustainable economic growth. Fuel poverty, conceptualized as the household's inability to meet its fundamental energy needs, is a pervasive issue in developing and developed economies (Kearns et al., 2019; Primc et al., 2019; Lin and Wang, 2020; Karpinska and Śmiech, 2020).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While climate change looms large in undermining efforts to eradicate extreme poverty, ambitious climate policies could place a financial burden on the world's middle classes through higher food and energy prices.Achieving sustainability goals and effectively limiting global warming necessitate aggressive decarbonization of industrialized countries, but also leaves relatively limited space for energy growth. However, the ability of developing nations to improve the living standards of the world's poor under these conditions is a critical concern.&lt;/p&gt;

items.description:
&lt;p&gt;Rising energy and housing costs for poor households have fueled energy policy debate in recent years. The availability of affordable, reliable, and sustainable energy service are essential to sustain well-being, which is also a prerequisite for achieving SDG7 and specific other SDGs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Further, reliable access to energy services is crucial for reducing various forms of poverty and sustainable economic growth. Fuel poverty, conceptualized as the household's inability to meet its fundamental energy needs, is a pervasive issue in developing and developed economies (Kearns et al., 2019; Primc et al., 2019; Lin and Wang, 2020; Karpinska and Śmiech, 2020).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While climate change looms large in undermining efforts to eradicate extreme poverty, ambitious climate policies could place a financial burden on the world's middle classes through higher food and energy prices.Achieving sustainability goals and effectively limiting global warming necessitate aggressive decarbonization of industrialized countries, but also leaves relatively limited space for energy growth. However, the ability of developing nations to improve the living standards of the world's poor under these conditions is a critical concern.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Guest editors:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fateh Belaïd&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;em&gt;King Abdullah Petroleum Studies and Research Center, Saudi Arabia&lt;br&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ramzi Benkraiem&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Audencia Business School, France&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Stéphane Goutte&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;em&gt;UMI_SOURCE, University Paris-Saclay France&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Khaled Guesmi&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;em&gt;CRECC – Paris School of Business, France&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special issue information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After the economic ravages of COVID-19, low-income countries are experiencing a more acute and long-lasting downturn that has increased poverty around the world and reversed recent trends in reducing inequality. According to the World Bank estimations, between 88 and 115 million people fell into extreme poverty in 2020, and this figure will reach between 119 and 124 million in 2021 (WB, 2020). Further, fuel poverty is associated with cold homes and adverse health outcomes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The challenge of addressing fuel vulnerability and poor energy efficient home-related negative health impacts is fundamental to improving the quality of life of many households by making their homes warmer and more efficient (Simshauser, 2021; Simshauser, 2021). Furthermore, reducing fuel poverty could substantially enhance health outcomes, reduce inequalities in health, as well as make an essential contribution to tackling residential greenhouse emissions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Despite the growing body of knowledge regarding fuel poverty assessment and the main factors driving fuel poverty phenomenon, gaps in the evidence remain (Bélaïd, 2018). Further research is required to investigate the fuel poor's attitudes to energy efficiency and how they perceive their energy situation (Kearns et al., 2019).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Within this context, this special issue's primary purpose is to amalgamate the high-quality research work on fuel poverty and energy vulnerability. The focus will be on the challenges, strategies, and lessons learned in recent years both in developing and developed countries. This special issue's specific objective is to understand the role of energy prices, housing characteristics, and socio-economic features in shaping the fuel poverty phenomenon.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;More precisely, it aims at providing an international overview of the many facets of fuel poverty, including domestic energy consumption, well-being, behavioral change, and energy efficiency deployment as an instrument for fuel poverty mitigation. To derive policy discussion/recommendations, the special issue will contain state-of-art policy, theoretical and empirical advances to examine and document fuel poverty's economic, health, and well-being implications.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A very holistic vision is more than ever necessary to combine ambitious climate policies with effort to alleviate energy poverty. The special issue will discuss innovative approaches and key policy measures to optimize lessons learned in tackling energy poverty and leverage them as the backbone of resilient and well-being economic model. Besides helping to gain a comprehensive overview of the scope of the energy poverty phenomenon, the special issue may also act as a vector to stimulate public engagement and disseminate information and best practices among policymakers, public and private stakeholders.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One of the expected impact of the special issue is to help policy-makers and practitioners to navigate the global fuel poverty agenda, provide a map of existing works and case studies, and recommend promising avenues for future research. This will inform the energy policy-making process within the framework of the sustainable development goals objectives and the continuous energy system transformation. Further, the SI will provide a holistic examination of fuel poverty issues and challenges and how they are being addressed by identifying, diagnosing, and tackling these challenges.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Theoretical robustness, scientific innovation, and potential policy applicability to energy poverty alleviation are the three major criteria for a paper to be considered for publication. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Contributions to this special issue are expected to cover the following topics (but are not limited to):&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;- Definition and energy poverty assessment- Exposure and risk to energy poverty: Examining the extent of the energy precariousness and its&lt;br&gt;predominant causal factors&lt;br&gt;- Climate policy and insights into energy poverty&lt;br&gt;- Ambitious climate policy with efforts to reduce energy poverty&lt;br&gt;- Energy poverty eradication in a carbon-constrained world&lt;br&gt;- Socio-economic inequalities in energy poverty before and during the COVID-19 pandemic&lt;br&gt;- Capacity and the energy-poor willingness to pay for improving their housing energy performance&lt;br&gt;- Impact of climate change policy on inequality and energy access&lt;br&gt;- The new era of the energy transition in the building sector&lt;br&gt;- Drivers and barriers of energy consumption and energy efficiency&lt;br&gt;- The role of energy efficiency in enhancing well-being and achieving sustainability goals&lt;br&gt;- Challenges, investment opportunities, financing and technological innovations in energy efficiency&lt;br&gt;- The role of uncertainty in shaping individual preferences for residential energy renovation decision&lt;br&gt;- The cost-effectiveness of energy efficiency implementation measures in the residential sector&lt;br&gt;- Energy poverty, health &amp; welfare benefits of energy efficiency&lt;br&gt;- Investment and individual preference for energy efficiency purchase decisions&lt;br&gt;- Economic Inequality and Household Energy Consumption&lt;br&gt;- Fuel poverty and energy policy: Challenges and solutions&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manuscript submission information:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You are invited to submit your manuscript from&lt;strong&gt; Jan 1st, 2023&lt;/strong&gt; until&lt;strong&gt; June 30th, &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2023&lt;/strong&gt;. Any questions about the special issue can be directed to the Managing Guest Editor: Stephane Goutte (&lt;a href="mailto:stephane.goutte@uvsq.fr"&gt;stephane.goutte@uvsq.fr&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The journal’s submission platform (&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.editorialmanager.com/jepo/default1.aspx" target="_blank"&gt;Editorial Manager&lt;sup&gt;®&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/a&gt;) will be available for receiving submissions to this Special Issue from Jan 1st, 2023 on. Please refer to the &lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.elsevier.com/journals/energy-policy/0301-4215/guide-for-authors" target="_blank"&gt;Guide for Authors&lt;/a&gt; to prepare your manuscript and select the article type of “&lt;strong&gt;VSI: Energy Poverty&lt;/strong&gt;” when submitting your manuscript online on the submission platform. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;All contributions will be initially assessed by the editor and the guest editors for suitability for the journal. Papers deemed suitable are then typically sent to a minimum of two independent expert reviewers to assess the article's scientific quality.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Why publish in this Special Issue?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Special Issue articles are published together on ScienceDirect, making it incredibly easy for other researchers to discover your work.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Special content articles are downloaded on ScienceDirect twice as often within the first 24 months than articles published in regular issues.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Special content articles attract 20% more citations in the first 24 months than articles published in regular issues.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;All articles in this special issue will be reviewed by no fewer than two independent experts to ensure the quality, originality and novelty of the work published.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn more about the benefits of publishing in a special issue: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interested in becoming a guest editor? Discover the benefits of guest-editing a special issue and the valuable contribution that you can make to your field: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;References:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Belaïd, F., 2018. Exposure and risk to fuel poverty in France: Examining the extent of the fuel precariousness and its salient determinants. &lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt;, 114, pp.189-200.​&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Karpinska, L. and Śmiech, S., 2020. Conceptualising housing costs: The hidden face of energy poverty in Poland. &lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt;, 147, p.111819.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Kearns, A., Whitley, E. and Curl, A., 2019. Occupant behaviour as a fourth driver of fuel poverty (aka warmth &amp; energy deprivation). &lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt;, 129, pp.1143-1155.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Kearns, A., Whitley, E. and Curl, A., 2019. Occupant behaviour as a fourth driver of fuel poverty (aka warmth &amp; energy deprivation). &lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt;, 129, pp.1143-1155.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Lin, B. and Wang, Y., 2020. Does energy poverty really exist in China? From the perspective of residential electricity consumption. &lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt;, 143, p.111557.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Primc, K., Slabe-Erker, R. and Majcen, B., 2019. Constructing energy poverty profiles for an effective energy policy. &lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt;, 128, pp.727-734.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Simshauser, P., 2021. Vulnerable households and fuel poverty: Measuring the efficiency of policy targeting in Queensland. &lt;em&gt;Energy Economics&lt;/em&gt;, 101, p.105405.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Simshauser, P., 2021. Vulnerable households and fuel poverty: Measuring the efficiency of policy targeting in Queensland. &lt;em&gt;Energy Economics&lt;/em&gt;, 101, p.105405.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Keywords:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Energy poverty; Energy demand; Energy efficiency; Climate change; COVID; Sustainability; Economic welfare; Inequality; Energy Security&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn more about the benefits of publishing in a special issue: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/authors/submit-your-paper/special-issues&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interested in becoming a guest editor? Discover the benefits of guest editing a special issue and the valuable contribution that you can make to your field: &lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors"&gt;https://www.elsevier.com/editors/role-of-an-editor/guest-editors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A review by &lt;a href="https://forschung.boku.ac.at/fis/suchen.person_uebersicht?sprache_in=en&amp;menue_id_in=101&amp;id_in=100653"&gt;Nikolaus Muellner&lt;/a&gt; and his colleagues from the University of Natural Resources and Life Sciences in Vienna, Austria, examines different nuclear energy growth scenarios to estimate its potential to curb CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; emissions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Using nuclear power to produce electricity is discussed as a potential solution to climate change but scientists disagree on the role it will play in lowering emissions. Some recent studies suggest that it could become the backbone of electricity production, at least replacing all coal-fired power plants, for example, while others advocate for a non-nuclear future or simply maintaining the nuclear power facilities that currently exist.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Muellner and the team start by looking at current national energy plans and their projections of future nuclear generating capacity while later considering other scenarios that involve introducing nuclear energy as a way to curb climate change. They also examine the uranium resources that would be required in the next 20 years for different scenarios.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To tackle the climate crisis, global warming needs to be limited to well below 2°C as outlined in the &lt;a href="https://unfccc.int/process-and-meetings/the-paris-agreement/the-paris-agreement"&gt;Paris Agreement&lt;/a&gt;, the internationally-agreed treaty adopted in 2015. Sources of energy that rely on fossil fuels therefore need to be substituted as much and as quickly as possible with cleaner alternatives to achieve this goal.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The most important takeaway from this work, however, is that nuclear power plays a very limited role in mitigating climate change, which is unlikely to change in the future. Using nuclear power is not expected to avoid more than 2 to 3% of total global greenhouse gas emissions annually between 2020 and 2040.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Furthermore, nuclear power cannot be expanded to become the main source of electricity production in the future due to the amount of uranium that would be needed. Uranium mining would have to increase, which would not be feasible due to limits on production and available reserves in the ground.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The authors also note that current levels of nuclear power production are likely to be maintained by extending the lifetime of existing reactors. However, it is also possible that they will be phased out completely due to their limited climate benefits and the potential for catastrophic accidents that would release radioactive materials. They conclude that ultimately, society will have to decide on these trade-offs.  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;Article details&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;N. Muellner et al. “&lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421521002330"&gt;Nuclear energy – The solution to climate change?&lt;/a&gt;” &lt;a href="https://www.journals.elsevier.com/energy-policy"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (2021)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
	Congress has provided federal agencies mechanisms whereby they can ﬁnance energy eﬃciency and renewable energy projects using private money. However, because the federal government&#39;s borrowing rate is lower than that of private entities, the energy projects could be performed at a lower cost than at present. Despite potential savings to the government of well over $100 million dollars per year, this does not occur. A recent &lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt; article looks into some of the reasons why.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.enpol.2017.09.020" target="_blank"&gt;The ineﬃcient ﬁnancing of federal agency energy projects&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
	Michael E. Canes&lt;br&gt;
	Energy Policy (Volume 111, December 2017)&lt;/p&gt;

