items.description:
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;em&gt;Two apparently contradictory studies come together with recommendations&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Power stored in electric cars could be sent back to the grid &ndash; thereby supporting the grid and acting as a potential storage for clean energy &ndash; but it will only be economically viable if we upgrade the system first. In a new paper in &lt;a href="https://www.journals.elsevier.com/energy-policy" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, two scientists show how their seemingly contradictory findings actually point to the same outcome and recommendations: that pumping energy back into the grid using today&rsquo;s technology can damage car batteries, but with improvements in the system it has the potential to provide valuable clean energy &ndash; and improve battery life in the process.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;br&gt;
	&lt;strong&gt;SHORT COMMUNICATION &ndash; OPEN ACCESS&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.enpol.2017.11.015" target="_blank"&gt;The viability of vehicle-to-grid operations from a battery technology and policy perspective&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
	Kotub Uddin, Matthieu Dubarry, Mark B. Glick&lt;br&gt;
	&lt;em&gt;Energy Policy, Volume 113, February 2018, Pages 342&ndash;347&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;br&gt;
	&lt;strong&gt;READ MORE&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/about/press-releases/research-and-journals/energy-from-electric-cars-could-power-our-lives-but-only-if-we-improve-the-system" target="_blank"&gt;Energy from electric cars could power our lives &ndash; but only if we improve the system&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
	&lt;em&gt;Elsevier Press Release, Oxford, November 22, 2017&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
	A recent cross-cutting study published in Energy Policy has received media attention.&nbsp; According to the new study by researchers at the University of Sussex, a lack of consumer engagement, insufficient information, and inadequate attention to vulnerability has slowed down the UK roll-out of energy smart meters.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The &pound;11 billion smart meter programme, which is supported by a &pound;100-million marketing campaign, has not met its targets due to consumer apathy and confusion, especially in the case of vulnerable people, say the researchers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The full research article, &lt;a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.enpol.2017.07.037" target="_blank"&gt;Vulnerability and resistance in the United Kingdom&#39;s smart meter transition&lt;/a&gt; by Benjamin K. Sovacool, Paula Kivimaa, Sabine Hielscher, Kirsten Jenkins, is available free online on ScienceDirect until end-September 2017.&lt;br&gt;
	&lt;br&gt;
	Read more about this research:&lt;br&gt;
	&lt;br&gt;
	&lt;a href="http://www.sussex.ac.uk/newsandevents/pressrelease/id/41630" target="_blank"&gt;&lsquo;Confusion and resistance&rsquo; slows down UK smart meter roll-out&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Press Release, University of Sussex, September 18, 2017&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;
	&lt;a href="https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/ed-miliband-smart-meter-energy-scheme-blows-a-fuse-knjfsf3jb"&gt;Ed Miliband smart meter energy scheme blows a fuse: A new study warns of &lsquo;risk of descending into chaos&rsquo;&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;em&gt;The Times, September 17, 2017&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

