&lt;p&gt;Extended abstract submission deadline 17 February 2023&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Discount registration deadline 31 March 2023&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/events/conferences/international-conference-on-algal-biomass-biofuels-and-bioproducts?utm_campaign=STMJ_1675074413_CONF_NEWS_AB&amp;utm_medium=WEB&amp;utm_source=WEB&amp;dgcid=STMJ_1675074413_CONF_NEWS_AB" data-anchor="?utm_campaign=STMJ_1675074413_CONF_NEWS_AB&amp;utm_medium=WEB&amp;utm_source=WEB&amp;dgcid=STMJ_1675074413_CONF_NEWS_AB"&gt;VISIT THE CONFERENCE SITE&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The International Conference on Algal Biomass, Biofuels and Bioproducts (AlgalBBB) will take place in-person, &lt;strong&gt;12–14 June 2023, &lt;/strong&gt;at the Waikoloa Beach Marriott Resort, Waikoloa Beach, Hawaii, USA. We are excited to be able to provide this much-awaited opportunity for the algae research community to meet in-person and discuss the very latest research and technologies and to interact with leaders in the field.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;AlgalBBB places a major emphasis on the latest unpublished technical and scientific results, along with discussion and direct interactions with broad spectrum scientists and engineers, funding sponsors, and leaders in the field from all over the world. The conference presents the work of the algae research community through a balanced set of oral presentations and posters selected from the best submissions to the conference. Our list of keynote and invited speakers includes funding agency sponsors, key industry players, and top scientists and engineers from the international community.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The conference will cover all areas of emerging technologies in all areas of algal research, including microalgae, macroalgae, and cyanobacteria: biology, biotechnology, biomass production, cultivation, harvesting, extraction, biorefinery, feedstock conversion into fuels, high value products, econometrics, and sustainability analyses.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In 2023, we look forward to hearing about the new emphasis on seaweed-based systems, engineering advances, molecular characterization technologies (e.g., genomics, proteomics, metabolomics), strain engineering technologies for biofuels and high value products and&lt;br&gt;pharmaceuticals, biomaterials, photobioreactor design and control systems, and new technologies in characterization and analysis, among others.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;AlgalBBB themes:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Algal Biotechnology - Molecular Engineering&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Algal Biology - Biodiversity and Bioprospecting of Algae for Biofuels and Bioproducts&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Algal Biotechnology - Metabolic Regulation of Algae for Biofuels and Bioproducts&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Algal Cultivation - Phototrophic Systems in Open Ponds&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Algal Cultivation - Phototrophic Systems in Photobioreactors&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Algal Cultivation - Heterotrophic Systems, including utilization of waste waters for algal production&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Bioreactor Design, Engineering and Control&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Algal Harvesting and Extraction Systems&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Engineering of Biorefinery Systems, Technologies, and End-to-end Integration&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;New Technologies in Support of Algal Research - Areas of Separation, Refining, Detection, Characterization and Analysis&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Engineering Technologies for Algal Biofuels - Thermal Catalytic and Non-Catalytic, and Enzymatic systems&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Bioproducts from Algae Including High-Value Products and Co-products&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Life Cycle, Technoeconomic, and Sustainability Modeling and Analysis of Algal Production and Fuel Cycle Systems&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Nutrient Recycling and Management&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Algal Biology – Improving photosynthetic growth and biomass productivity&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You can feel confident when submitting your abstract to AlgalBBB 2023 that&lt;br&gt;we will provide a high-quality, peer-reviewed programme in which to&lt;br&gt;showcase your research.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Conference hashtag #algalbbb&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.elsevier.com/events/conferences/international-conference-on-algal-biomass-biofuels-and-bioproducts?utm_campaign=STMJ_1675074413_CONF_NEWS_AB&amp;utm_medium=WEB&amp;utm_source=WEB&amp;dgcid=STMJ_1675074413_CONF_NEWS_AB" data-anchor="?utm_campaign=STMJ_1675074413_CONF_NEWS_AB&amp;utm_medium=WEB&amp;utm_source=WEB&amp;dgcid=STMJ_1675074413_CONF_NEWS_AB"&gt;VISIT THE CONFERENCE SITE&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="https://api.journals.elsevier.com/media/crvhmoaz/algalbbb_150x150.jpg" alt="Algalbbb"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The taxes and levies on energy prices have a major impact on energy use and the funds available to governments to promote reduced dependency on fossil fuels. A new &lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0301421522005869" target="_blank"&gt;study&lt;/a&gt;, published in &lt;em&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/energy-policy" target="_blank"&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;, reveals significant imbalances in the way five European countries apportion fuel taxes, and indicates that environmental costs are seldom well-reflected in energy prices.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The research, led by &lt;a rel="noopener" href="http://www.janrosenow.com/index.html" target="_blank"&gt;Jan Rosenow&lt;/a&gt; at the &lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.raponline.org/" target="_blank"&gt;Regulatory Assistance Project&lt;/a&gt;, compared the structure of energy taxes and levies across Europe, with particular focus on five countries: Belgium, Germany, Italy, Spain and the UK.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The study explains methods for assessing existing taxes and levies in the context of the environmental and social costs of different heating sources, and also presents a method for calculating the effects of suggested tax and levy policy reforms.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Applying these methods to current arrangements in the five countries reveals significant imbalances in how fuel taxes and levies are shared out. It also indicates that environmental costs are rarely well-reflected in energy prices, and that the costs of energy transition programmes and related social policies are overwhelmingly borne by electricity consumers.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The authors offer four examples of reforms that would rebalance taxes and levies between electricity and heating fuels. These suggestions could drive the changes in energy sources that governments wish to encourage as part of plans to decarbonise energy supplies.&lt;br&gt;An optimum mix of reforms would see higher fossil fuel taxes and lower electricity taxes, reflecting the respective environmental costs, along with a redistribution of levy costs from electricity consumers to taxpayers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The reforms would be in line with the basic principle of efficient taxation, allowing prices to reflect all costs related to production, including environmental costs. They would also more effectively allow money raised through general taxation to fund relevant social spending, including subsidies to encourage the desired transition to more environmentally friendly energy supply options.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Article details: &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;Rosenow, J.et al.: “&lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0301421522005869"&gt;Clean heating: Reforming taxes and levies on heating fuels in Europe&lt;/a&gt;,” &lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt; (2022)&lt;/p&gt;

items.intro:
&lt;div class="col-sm-9"&gt;
&lt;p class="form-control-static element-with-newlines"&gt;Foreign direct investment (FDI) tends to reduce pollutant emissions, a new systematic review of the literature concludes. This new meta-analysis published Energy Policy aims to explain why the conclusions of the published studies on this issue are so inconsistent.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

items.description:
&lt;p&gt;FDI occurs when a company or investor buys an interest in a company in another country. It has many significant economic benefits, such as contributing to economic growth, providing employment and spreading the use of advanced technologies. However, there is widespread concern that FDI also has a negative environmental effect because it increases the emission of pollutants such as carbon dioxide (CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;), sulphur dioxide (SO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;) and nitrogen oxides (N0&lt;sub&gt;𝑥&lt;/sub&gt;). Nevertheless, the conclusions of published studies vary considerably, both in terms of whether FDI increases or decreases these emissions and in the magnitude of the change.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The review’s authors, &lt;a href="https://www.eur.nl/en/people/binyam-afewerk-demena" title="https://www.eur.nl/en/people/binyam-afewerk-demena"&gt;Binyam Afewerk Demena&lt;/a&gt; from Erasmus University Rotterdam in the Netherlands and &lt;a href="https://www.uoguelph.ca/fare/users/safesorg" title="https://www.uoguelph.ca/fare/users/safesorg"&gt;Sylvanus Kwaku Afesorgbor&lt;/a&gt; from the University of Guelph in Canada, aim to gain a clearer overall picture of the literature by analysing the results from 65 studies. These studies are very heterogeneous in that they vary considerably in terms of the countries studied, the emissions measured and the econometric methods used.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The meta-analysis shows that the underlying effect of FDI on environmental emissions is close to zero. However, after accounting for the heterogeneity of the studies, it indicates that FDI significantly reduces environmental emissions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The authors also note that the impact of FDI is variable, both in a country’s level of development (the reduction of emissions is higher for developed countries) and for the pollutant measured (such as being higher for SO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; than CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;). They thus conclude that a country’s environmental policies should be specific to that country and to the pollutant they are aiming to control.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Article details:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Demena, B.A. and Afesorgbor, S.K.: “&lt;a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.enpol.2019.111192" title="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.enpol.2019.111192"&gt;The effect of FDI on environmental emissions: Evidence from a meta-analysis&lt;/a&gt;,” &lt;a href="https://www.journals.elsevier.com/energy-policy" title="https://www.journals.elsevier.com/energy-policy"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (2020)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Nearly three billion people still rely on harmful, smoky cooking fuels such as wood, dung and kerosene. Despite concerted efforts to introduce cleaner methods, the transition to clean household fuel remains slow and a huge acceleration will be needed if the UN’s &lt;a href="https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/sdg7" data-cke-saved-href="https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/sdg7"&gt;Sustainable Development Goal 7&lt;/a&gt;, which calls for ‘affordable, reliable, sustainable and modern energy for all’, is to be met by 2030.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A&lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421520302196" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421520302196"&gt; new review&lt;/a&gt; by &lt;a href="https://www.jhsph.edu/faculty/directory/profile/635/anita-vernekar-shankar" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.jhsph.edu/faculty/directory/profile/635/anita-vernekar-shankar"&gt;Anita Shankar&lt;/a&gt; of&lt;a href="https://www.jhsph.edu/" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.jhsph.edu/"&gt; Johns Hopkins University&lt;/a&gt;, Baltimore, MD, Ashlinn Quinn of the US National Institutes of Health, and colleagues in the US, UK and Mexico from the &lt;a href="https://www.fic.nih.gov/About/Staff/Policy-Planning-Evaluation/Pages/clean-cooking-implementation-science-network.aspx" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.fic.nih.gov/About/Staff/Policy-Planning-Evaluation/Pages/clean-cooking-implementation-science-network.aspx"&gt;Clean Cooking Implementation Science Network&lt;/a&gt; discusses case studies from Africa and sub-Saharan Africa; sets out the main reasons why reducing pollution from cooking is proving so difficult; and offers a blueprint for overcoming these barriers. This is published in the Elsevier journal &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/energy-policy" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/energy-policy"&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Numerous programmes to roll out clean fuels, such as liquefied petroleum gas (LPG), into poor homes have met with only partial success; the householders adopt new fuels alongside established, more polluting methods. This phenomenon, in which a novel cooking technology is simply added to the traditional ones, is known as ‘stove stacking’ and it is ubiquitous. The same thing occurs in richer households whenever a microwave or slow cooker is added to the existing repertoire of kitchen equipment.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Shankar, Quinn and their co-authors set out economic, behavioural and cultural reasons why, in the low-income context, cleaner devices and fuels are ‘stacked’ on top of more polluting ones. It is sometimes a simple matter of cost, but wood stoves, for instance, often remain in use even when incomes rise or the cost of cleaner fuels plummets. Depending on the setting, other reasons include excessive travel time to obtain clean fuel (e.g. to exchange LPG cylinders), stoves that were ill-suited to larger cooking volumes and/or specific cooking tasks, and the secondary room-heating advantage of wood burning.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Given the reality of stove stacking, the authors propose seven principles for ‘clean stack design’ and policy focused on discontinuation of traditional stove use and a shift towards ‘cleaner stacks’ of fuels and cooking devices. The aim is to enable households to transition away from polluting fuels and practices and reduce exposure to air pollution in the home and nearby environment.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Article details:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;Shankar, A.V. et al. (2020). ‘&lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421520302196" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421520302196"&gt;Everybody stacks: Lessons from household energy case studies to inform design principles for clean energy transitions&lt;/a&gt;’, Energy Policy (2020).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The world of 1974 in which the &lt;a href="https://www.iea.org/" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.iea.org/"&gt;International Energy Agency&lt;/a&gt; (IEA) was set up was very different to that of today. The IEA was established after the 1970s oil crisis to regulate the supply of oil to large oil-consuming countries, particularly during future crises, and it has generally been viewed as the predominant international organisation in global energy. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, recent changes to the balance of international power and the range of energy sources used have left the IEA looking outdated and vulnerable. In a &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0301421520302056" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0301421520302056"&gt;far-reaching review&lt;/a&gt; in the Elsevier journal &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/energy-policy" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/energy-policy"&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="http://christiandownie.com/" data-cke-saved-href="http://christiandownie.com/"&gt;Christian Downie&lt;/a&gt; from the &lt;a href="https://www.anu.edu.au/" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.anu.edu.au/"&gt;Australian National University&lt;/a&gt;, Canberra, sets out the threats facing the IEA today, examines how it is adapting to respond to them, and draws some broader lessons for international organisations.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The threats facing the IEA today can be grouped into three. Firstly, its membership structure which is tied to that of the &lt;a href="http://www.oecd.org/" data-cke-saved-href="http://www.oecd.org/"&gt;OECD&lt;/a&gt; looks increasingly old-fashioned. The BRIC nations of Brazil, Russia, India and China are all now in the top 10 energy-consuming countries, but they are not in the OECD and, therefore, not entitled to join the IEA. Secondly, a mandate narrowly focused on oil security seems both outdated and short-sighted in view of the threat of climate change and the need for a transition to clean energy sources. And thirdly, the field is becoming crowded with an ‘alphabet soup’ of newer international organisations focusing on energy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The strategy that the IEA has drawn up to survive and thrive in this new world has four strands. It is reaching out to prominent emerging economies by enrolling ‘association members’ and broadening its reach to include renewable energy and energy efficiency. The other two strands involve acting assertively to defend its territory from ‘invasion’ by newer organisations, while working more closely with large international organisations outside energy, particularly the &lt;a href="https://g20.org/en/Pages/home.aspx" data-cke-saved-href="https://g20.org/en/Pages/home.aspx"&gt;G20&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The initial success of these strategies underlines the fact that organisations like the IEA are able to employ a certain amount of strategic independence from their member states and that this can help them thrive. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Article details&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Downie, C.: &lt;a href="http://nonsolus/st@r/admin/tasks/Strategies%20for%20Survival:%20The%20International%20Energy%20Agency%E2%80%99s%20response%20to%20a%20new%20world.%20Energy%20Policy" data-cke-saved-href="http://nonsolus/st@r/admin/tasks/Strategies%20for%20Survival:%20The%20International%20Energy%20Agency%E2%80%99s%20response%20to%20a%20new%20world.%20Energy%20Policy"&gt;Strategies for Survival: The International Energy Agency’s response to a new world. Energy Policy&lt;/a&gt; (2020)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Improvements to cars and small trucks in the US have doubled vehicle fuel economy since 1975. An &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0301421520302627?via%3Dihub" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0301421520302627?via%3Dihub"&gt;article &lt;/a&gt;published in Elsevier’s &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0301421520302627?via%3Dihub" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0301421520302627?via%3Dihub"&gt;Energy Policy &lt;/a&gt;in April 2020 estimates that this has led to savings of two trillion gallons of fuel, 17 billion tonnes of CO2 emissions and 4.9 trillion dollars.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The study showed the average car &lt;a href="https://www.globalfueleconomy.org/transport/gfei/autotool/approaches/information/test_cycles.asp" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.globalfueleconomy.org/transport/gfei/autotool/approaches/information/test_cycles.asp"&gt;test-cycle&lt;/a&gt; has increased from 15.7&lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuel_economy_in_automobiles" data-cke-saved-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuel_economy_in_automobiles"&gt;mpg&lt;/a&gt; in 1975 to 39.1mpg in 2018. These figures are mirrored by fuel consumption changes in small trucks. However, transferring these lab figures to real on-road fuel savings has been a challenge.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Real-world improvements are gradual as new, more efficient vehicles replace older, less efficient ones. The paper’s authors, based at the &lt;a href="https://www.utk.edu/" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.utk.edu/"&gt;University of Tennessee &lt;/a&gt;and the US&lt;a href="https://www.nrel.gov/" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.nrel.gov/"&gt; National Renewable Energy Laboratory&lt;/a&gt;, also had to consider actual on-road conditions. When these two factors were taken into account, adjusted fuel economy gains closely matched estimates by the Federal Highway Administration based on traffic counts and motor fuel tax records. The researchers were able to show that mpg gains on regulatory tests have led to proportional on-road improvements. The study also revealed that changes in driver behaviour due to improved fuel economy of vehicles had little effect on fuel savings. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The adjusted fuel savings of two trillion gallons of fuel between 1975 and 2018 exceeds the total fuel use of all US light-duty vehicles (cars and small trucks) from 2004 to 2018, the authors noted. And the reduction of 17 trillion tonnes of CO2 emissions is more than all US gross CO2 emissions from all sources between 2016 and 2018.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Overall, the team estimates that, over the 43 years investigated, four-fifths of fuel savings are due to improved fuel economy and greenhouse gas standards. Only one-fifth of savings can be attributed to gasoline price increases.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Article details:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;Greene, D.L., Sims, C.B., Muratori, M.: “&lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0301421520302627?via%3Dihub" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0301421520302627?via%3Dihub"&gt;Two trillion gallons: Fuel savings from fuel economy improvements to US light-duty vehicles, 1975-2018&lt;/a&gt;,” Energy Policy (2020).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Three researchers from Germany’s &lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.isi.fraunhofer.de/en.html" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.isi.fraunhofer.de/en.html"&gt;Fraunhofer Institute for Systems and Innovation Research&lt;/a&gt; and Russia's &lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.hse.ru/en/" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.hse.ru/en/"&gt;Higher School of Economics&lt;/a&gt; have proposed a methodological framework for comparing and assessing how European countries are progressing towards the EU’s 2050 low carbon targets.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In a paper published in &lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421519302204?via%3Dihub#!" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421519302204?via%3Dihub#!"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.hse.ru/en/staff/nmikova" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.hse.ru/en/staff/nmikova"&gt;Nadezhda Mikova&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.isi.fraunhofer.de/en/competence-center/energiepolitik-energiemaerkte/mitarbeiter/eichhammer.html" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.isi.fraunhofer.de/en/competence-center/energiepolitik-energiemaerkte/mitarbeiter/eichhammer.html"&gt;Wolfgang Eichhammer&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.isi.fraunhofer.de/en/competence-center/energiepolitik-energiemaerkte/mitarbeiter/pfluger.html" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.isi.fraunhofer.de/en/competence-center/energiepolitik-energiemaerkte/mitarbeiter/pfluger.html"&gt;Benjamin Pfluger&lt;/a&gt; present their new framework alongside an analysis of current progress in six EU countries. They lay out recommendations for taking “a more harmonised approach” to scenarios for decarbonisation that will improve “consistency and transparency”.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In 2011, the European Commission published a &lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://ec.europa.eu/clima/sites/clima/files/strategies/2050/docs/roadmap_fact_sheet_en.pdf" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://ec.europa.eu/clima/sites/clima/files/strategies/2050/docs/roadmap_fact_sheet_en.pdf"&gt;Roadmap for moving to a competitive low carbon economy in 2050&lt;/a&gt;. The roadmap states that “The EU should achieve an overall 80% reduction in domestic emissions by 2050. To achieve this long-term target cost-efficiently, the EU should reduce its domestic emissions by 40% and 60% by 2030 and 2040, respectively.”&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The team’s framework has been designed to compare and measure how countries are progressing towards these targets. It is based on ten assessment characteristics, including ambitiousness of targets, relations with other (European) countries, and stakeholder involvement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To evaluate current progress, the researchers looked at six north-west European countries: the Netherlands, Germany, France, Denmark, the UK and Belgium. They found different levels of progress and note that development is still “spontaneous and disjointed”. In response, the authors present concrete proposals for improvement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To achieve the 2050 targets, countries need to use “long-term thinking”; they need to design clear policies and energy scenarios with specific aims. Key to success are “collaboration and joint efforts”. EU countries, the researchers point out, have close socio-economic relationships and climate change is a global concern, therefore, “scenarios cannot be isolated”.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The researchers also recommend an “interactive” approach to policymaking that includes government, business, academia, NGOs and the public. Further, non-technological solutions, such as encouraging lifestyle changes, should also be embraced.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Climate change is one of the 21st century’s most pressing challenges, monitoring and assessing what countries are doing about it is key to the success, or otherwise, of the world’s response.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Article details:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Mikova, N., et al.: "&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421519302204?via%3Dihub#!" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421519302204?via%3Dihub#!"&gt;Low-carbon energy scenarios 2050 in north-west European countries: Towards a more harmonised approach to achieve the EU targets&lt;/a&gt;," &lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt; (2019).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The concept of 'energy poverty', defined simply as the inability to heat the home to an acceptable level, was first introduced in the UK in the 1970s. However, this concept has only recently been taken on board by policymakers. Instead, general measures of deprivation are used as a proxy, with energy-specific interventions targeted to areas classed simply as 'deprived'.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This policy can only be effective if there is a strong relationship between energy poverty and overall deprivation. This hypothesis has frequently been questioned, and now researchers at the &lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.sheffield.ac.uk/" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sheffield.ac.uk/"&gt;University of Sheffield&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt;, UK, have shown it is false. Their study, '&lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421519301909" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421519301909"&gt;Examining the relationship between energy policy and measures of deprivation&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt;', was recently published in the Elsevier journal &lt;em&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/energy-policy" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/energy-policy"&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As an example, imagine a low-income family in social housing. It is quite likely they are not fuel poor as their home is small and relatively energy efficient (as required by law). But by targeting energy efficiency schemes based on deprivation, this home may receive insulation it doesn’t need, instead of support for tackling the root causes of deprivation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Marchand and his team measured the correlation between energy poverty and overall deprivation on a district by district level, restricting their analysis to England. Two numerical values were obtained for each of over 32,000 Lower Super Output Areas (LSOA) in England, each representing roughly 1500 individuals. Data on overall deprivation came from an Index of Multiple Deprivation published in 2010, and on energy poverty from the UK Government's own statistics published in 2012.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Correlating these together showed that the two datasets were essentially independent: some areas with little overall deprivation had high levels of energy poverty, and vice versa.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The researchers used this data to construct a matrix of energy poverty versus overall deprivation in which each LSOA was put into one of 25 categories depending on its position on the two scales. They proposed that using this to tailor interventions such as winter fuel payments would be more effective than using deprivation as a proxy for energy poverty.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Article details:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Marchand, R. et al. '&lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421519301909" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421519301909"&gt;Examining the relationship between energy poverty and measures of deprivation&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt;,' &lt;em&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/energy-policy" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/energy-policy"&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/em&gt; (2019)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Photovoltaic Solar Modules, thought to be one of the cleanest forms of energy, has dramatically increased in popularity in recent years due to a rapid reduction in the cost of this technology. In this article, researchers based at Massachusetts Institute of Technology carry out a detailed analysis of the reasons behind this cost reduction.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Amid so much bad news about climate change, it is easy to miss positive developments. Among these is the rapidly growing popularity of one of the 'cleanest' of all energy sources: photovoltaic solar modules. The surge in popularity has been accompanied by a rapid reduction in the cost of this technology, but the reasons for this were unclear. &lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="http://trancik.mit.edu/" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="http://trancik.mit.edu/"&gt;Jessika Trancik&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt; and her co-workers at &lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://idss.mit.edu/" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://idss.mit.edu/"&gt;Massachusetts Institute of Technology&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt;, USA carried out a detailed analysis of the reasons behind this cost reduction. Their paper, '&lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421518305196" target="_blank" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421518305196"&gt;Evaluating the causes of cost reduction in photovoltaic modules&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt;,' was published in the journal &lt;em&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/em&gt; in December 2018.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By developing a new mathematical model, the group found that energy conversion efficiency was the most important low-level driver of cost reduction between 1980 and 2001, but that manufacturing plant size became most important after 2001. Research and development (R&amp;D) and – in the later period – economies of scale have been the most important high-level factors. These mechanisms were enabled by public R&amp;D and policies that stimulate market growth. This research suggests that continuing public R&amp;D, as well as market-stimulating policies, can help support cost reductions going forward.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To reach these conclusions, the researchers divided the factors involved in cost reduction into two categories: high- and low-level. Low-level mechanisms explain the changes in solar module costs directly due to changes in the cost of silicon and other raw materials, plant size, yield and energy conversion efficiency. High-level mechanisms can be thought of as the drivers of low-level mechanisms and include public and private R&amp;D investment, 'learning by doing' and economies of scale.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The team hope their work will be useful in supporting further cost reductions in the decades to come. This will be essential if solar energy is to play a full part in the zero-carbon fuel environment that is needed to mitigate the worst effects of climate change.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Policy analysts in Finland contend that the term "renewable energy" should be ditched.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Abandoning the term "&lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renewable_energy" target="_blank" title="renewable energy" data-cke-saved-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renewable_energy"&gt;renewable energy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt;" may help the fight against &lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://climate.nasa.gov/evidence/" target="_blank" title="climate change" data-cke-saved-href="https://climate.nasa.gov/evidence/"&gt;climate change&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt;, say &lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://research.aalto.fi/portal/atte.harjanne.html" target="_blank" title="Atte Harjanne" data-cke-saved-href="https://research.aalto.fi/portal/atte.harjanne.html"&gt;Atte Harjanne&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt; and &lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://fi.linkedin.com/in/jmkorhonen" target="_blank" title="Janne M. Korhonen" data-cke-saved-href="https://fi.linkedin.com/in/jmkorhonen"&gt;Janne M. Korhonen&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt; in an &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421518308280" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421518308280"&gt;article&lt;/a&gt; in the journal &lt;em&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421518308280" target="_blank" title="Energy Policy" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421518308280"&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;“Renewable energy is a problematic concept that can misguide climate and energy debates and policy making,” says Harjanne, a doctoral researcher at &lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://www.aalto.fi/school-of-business" target="_blank" title="Aalto University School of Business" data-cke-saved-href="https://www.aalto.fi/school-of-business"&gt;Aalto University School of Business&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt; in Finland.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The pair analysed the history of the concept of renewable energy and provide examples of problematic issues regarding its use. They describe their work as being anchored in “institutional theory”, and focused on a problem of vocabulary rather than of science itself.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The problems the authors discuss are not based on criticism of the specific energy generation methods commonly described as “renewable”, but rather on how use of that term can hide the complexities of alternative policy options.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Harjanne acknowledges climate change as “the most pressing issue of our time.” He concludes, however, that the way the term “renewables” is used in language does not promote best understanding of the various solutions and their respective merits and disadvantages.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The authors’ argument centres on the great diversity of renewable energy sources, leading to the conclusion that lumping all renewable technologies together can limit the more valuable comparisons of the benefits and disadvantages of different energy generation methods in different situations.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;They suggest that if a technology can be described as renewable, that may shut down deeper analysis of how appropriate it actually is in any given circumstance.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Linking their analysis to &lt;u&gt;&lt;a rel="noopener" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sustainability" target="_blank" title="sustainability" data-cke-saved-href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sustainability"&gt;sustainability&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/u&gt;, the other key buzzword in the field, the authors argue that renewable does not necessarily mean sustainable. They point out, for example, that burning biomass to generate electricity may be sustainable in a small-scale local context but unsustainable in terms of the land use required to grow biomass on a large scale. Similarly, hydro-electric power generation can also have severe negative environmental impacts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Adverse impacts of other renewable energy sources, including geothermal, wind and solar energy, are also considered.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;“Rather than focussing on renewables, we should be looking at the actual measurable impacts of each technology,” says Harjanne. Such impacts include the level of carbon dioxide and other emissions, and the energy expended in creating the required technologies, such as wind turbines, solar panels or hydro-electric dams.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In place of what they consider the over-generalised use of the term “renewables”, Harjanne and Korhonen offer an alternative model that categorises energy generation systems according to their overall effect, focusing especially on the carbon dioxide released to the atmosphere.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;They present their model in a diagram they call a “carbon-combustion quadrant”. This emphasises low carbon content in the energy generating process and the lowest possible levels of combustion as the two key favourable factors for any technology.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The researchers claim that their alternative analysis is a much more subtle and useful approach than just decreeing that renewables are good and everything else is bad.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
	Some commentators have observed recently that vast quantities of oil and gas must remain in the ground because of anticipated action on climate change. A consequent fall in the share values of international oil companies may affect pensions, small investments, and even the stability of the financial system. It is reasoned that this justifies policy intervention, to provide more information to small investors.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	However, economist Robert Cairns at McGill University in Canada suggests in his article,&nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421518304208" target="_blank"&gt;Stranded oil of Erewhon&lt;/a&gt;, published in the journal&nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/energy-policy" target="_blank"&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&nbsp;(October 2018), that the technology of oil extraction and the options available to oil companies mean there is little basis for this concern. (Erewhon is a satirical, 19-century novel by Samuel Butler that takes place in the topsy-turvy land of Erewhon &ndash; which is &lsquo;Nowhere&rsquo; spelt, nearly exactly, backwards.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Both exploration and development in the oil industry are highly sensitive to its current price and to anticipations about future prices, with investments only made if there is good reason to expect that they will be profitable. The assets sunk in the oil industry have only limited susceptibility to stranding because of a feature particular to the industry &ndash; the natural decline of production from a well.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	By the time a climate policy is introduced, much of the value from developed reserves will have been paid back. Moreover, those reserves will remain competitive against new developments, which must be expected to pay back their newly incurred sunk costs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The transition may well be orderly, since comparable challenges in 2008 and 2014 have not given rise to stranded assets. Producers are now limiting attention to the most profitable opportunities for investment, and less profitable ones may never be developed.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	To the extent that oil companies are vulnerable to stranding, some of that vulnerability may already be discounted into the price of their shares. There is no reason to suppose that the market is not adequately pricing the risk of climatic action.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
	A team of researchers in the US has evaluated the likelihood of one or more foreign oil disruptions over the next 10 years, and estimates an approximately 80% probability of a significant disruption, with a region comprising the Persian Gulf countries (excluding Saudi Arabia) identified as the most risky area.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The probability of the size and duration of another oil disruption is critical to assessing oil market risk and estimating the value of any policy designed to limit the economic damages from sudden oil supply disruptions. Therefore the Energy Modeling Forum at Stanford University has developed a structured risk assessment framework, and evaluated the likelihood of one or more foreign oil disruptions over the next 10 years.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The new study,&nbsp;&lt;a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.enpol.2017.12.013" target="_blank"&gt;An updated assessment of oil market disruption risks&lt;/a&gt;, was recently published in the journal&nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.journals.elsevier.com/energy-policy" target="_blank"&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/a&gt;, as part of a Virtual Special Issue on &lsquo;Oil Supply Disruptions, US Economic Activity and Oil Security&rsquo;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Leading geopolitical, military and oil-market experts provided their expertise on the probability of different events occurring, and their corresponding link to major supply disruptions in key oil market regions. This panel concluded that current world events and energy markets have increased the likelihood of oil disruptions since 1996, but their combined judgment indicated a risk profile similar to the 2005 period. Moreover, their assessments indicate that lower oil price paths make net disruptions of any given size more likely.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The study evaluated five primary production regions: Saudi Arabia, Other Persian Gulf, Africa, Latin America, and Russian/Caspian States. Disruptions are defined as being net of offsets (e.g. OPEC spare capacity), with the notable exception that the US Strategic Petroleum Reserve (SPR) and other global emergency petroleum stocks are not included as a source of offsets.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	At least once during the 10-year time frame (2016&ndash;2025), there exists an approximately 80% probability of a net (of offsets) disruption of 2 million barrels per day or more lasting at least one month. While shorter disruptions are more likely, the framework captured longer duration disruptions of 6&ndash;18 months, and very long disruptions lasting longer than 18 months.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The article describes its approach to oil market disruption risk assessments in considerable detail, to allow others to grasp some of the benefits and challenges of adopting such a formal, structured evaluation of expert judgment. Additional studies applied more frequently would augment our understanding of oil supply risks, and could provide continuously updated insights for selecting appropriate strategies.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
	Vehicle-to-Grid (V2G) holds the promise of cheap, flexible and fast-responding energy storage through the use of electric vehicle (EV) batteries. Unfortunately, infrastructure, battery degradation and consumer awareness are only some of the challenges to a faster development of this technology.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	A new Open Access article in the journal &lt;a href="https://www.journals.elsevier.com/energy-policy" target="_blank"&gt;Energy Policy&lt;/a&gt;, by researchers at &lt;a href="http://btech.au.dk/en/research/research-groups-and-centres/cet" target="_blank"&gt;Aarhus University&lt;/a&gt; in Denmark and the &lt;a href="http://www.sussex.ac.uk/spru/research" target="_blank"&gt;University of Sussex&lt;/a&gt; in the UK, offers a qualitative comparative analysis to discuss the reasoning and arguments behind V2G incentives and policy mechanisms in the Nordic region.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The analysis &ndash; &lt;a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301421518300995" target="_blank"&gt;Promoting Vehicle to Grid (V2G) in the Nordic Region: Expert advice on policy mechanisms for accelerated diffusion&lt;/a&gt; &ndash; draws on a subsample of 227 interviews with transportation and electricity experts from 201 institutions and 17 cities across the region.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	A frequency analysis of the most coded V2G responses favoured an update of electricity market regulation &ndash; in particular in relation to electricity taxation and aggregator markets &ndash; and support for pilot projects. However, the analysis overall implies that V2G, in contrast to EVs, is a technology for the market and by the market: one that will develop on its own over time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	This analysis shows the debates around V2G and how its perspective differs by country, pending available frequency capacity, and flexible production (such as hydroelectric power).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The article calls for further development of flexible electricity markets, support for pilot projects, and attention to information and planning.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

